  abstract = {{\textcopyright} Copyright 2015 ACM.Pedestrian flow analysis using Wi-Fi packet sensors can easily collect the movement trajectories of individuals, has a high-resolution sensing ability, and is well suited to indoor operations. Thus it is regarded as one of the promising sensing technologies for Smart Cities targeting a variety of applications such as disaster prevention, the planning of commercial and barrier-free facilities, and monitoring people with disabilities. However, because Wi-Fi packet sensors cannot detect devices that have disabled their Wi-Fi functionality or people with no Wi-Fi devices, they can only probabilistically estimate the number of people in a target area. We conducted a two-month field experiment in a shopping mall, and derived a coefficient for estimating the actual number of people in the area by comparing the number of recognized devices in the mall, as counted by Wi-Fi packet sensors, with data from motion detectors placed at all of the mall's entrances and exits. In the calculation process, we separated the collected data into weekdays and holidays by considering the visiting patterns, and calculated an estimation coefficient   for the actual number of people. This gives the least absolute error between the observed values given by the Wi-Fi packet sensors and hourly data of motion detectors over the course of a week. The accuracy of   is evaluated by comparing known data from the motion detectors with the estimated people numbers calculated from the Wi-Fi packet sensor data. As a result, we demonstrate that the maximum error in the number of people in the mall for each hour, accumulated over a day, is less than 7.9{\%}.},
